{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599338"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:52:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:52:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15544"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15544"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.42,0.04,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8235"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61794"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8235"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47240"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"},{"type":"tags","id":"10106"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19913"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61794"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up of her hypothyroidism. During the consultation, she asks about how thyroid hormone actually works in the body. You decide to explain the concept of hormone receptors.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a cell surface receptor?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid hormone receptor","Tyrosine kinase receptor","Steroid hormone receptor","Vitamin D receptor","Retinoid X receptor"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECell surface receptors are proteins embedded in the plasma membrane that detect and respond to extracellular signals. They play crucial roles in cell signaling and communication. These receptors typically respond to molecules that cannot cross the cell membrane easily, such as peptide hormones, growth factors, and neurotransmitters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETyrosine kinase receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are classic examples of cell surface receptors. When activated by their ligands (such as insulin or growth factors), they undergo dimerization and auto-phosphorylation, leading to downstream signaling cascades. These receptors are essential for many cellular processes including growth, differentiation, and metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid hormone receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are nuclear receptors found inside cells, not on the cell surface. Thyroid hormones, being lipophilic, can pass through the cell membrane to bind these intracellular receptors, which then act as transcription factors to regulate gene expression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESteroid hormone receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are also nuclear receptors, not cell surface receptors. Like thyroid hormones, steroid hormones are lipophilic and enter cells to bind their receptors, which then modulate gene transcription.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D receptors\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003ERetinoid X receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are both nuclear receptors that function as transcription factors when bound to their respective ligands. They are not located on the cell surface.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the location and mechanism of different hormone receptors is crucial for comprehending hormone action and developing targeted therapies. While nuclear receptors typically respond to lipophilic hormones that can cross cell membranes, cell surface receptors generally respond to water-soluble signals that cannot enter cells directly.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cell surface receptors are membrane-bound proteins that respond to extracellular signals and initiate intracellular signaling cascades.","Tyrosine kinase receptors are cell surface receptors that phosphorylate specific tyrosine residues in response to ligand binding.","Nuclear receptors like steroid and thyroid hormone receptors are intracellular, not cell surface receptors."],"references":["Alberts B, Johnson A, Lewis J, et al. Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2002. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21054/","Marzvanyan A, Alhawaj AF. Physiology, Sensory Receptors. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539861/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47240"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15544"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47240"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T13:40:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T13:43:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8235"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61794"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relat